Explain the memory leak and dangling pointer issues in this list node deletion function, and write the corrected code:

```c
void delete_node(Node *head, int target) {
    Node *temp = head;
    while (temp != NULL) {
        if (temp->data == target) {
            free(temp);
            temp = temp->next; /* Dangling pointer dereference */
        }
    }
}
```

questionsAndAnswers.answer:
This code contains a dangling pointer dereference because 'temp->next' is accessed after 'temp' has been freed. It also does not update the linked list pointers, which can break the chain. The corrected implementation tracks the previous node and handles deletion safely:

```c
Node* delete_node_safe(Node *head, int target) {
    Node *temp = head;
    Node *prev = NULL;

    while (temp != NULL) {
        if (temp->data == target) {
            Node *to_delete = temp;
            if (prev == NULL) {
                head = temp->next;
            } else {
                prev->next = temp->next;
            }
            temp = temp->next;
            free(to_delete);
        } else {
            prev = temp;
            temp = temp->next;
        }
    }
    return head;
}
```

This function takes a buffer and performs a bitwise XOR operation on each byte using a dynamic key pattern. Applying the function a second time restores the original data:

